##### MF4: ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS OF SECONDARY PARTICLES           7325 1451
                                                                  7325 1451
The versatility of MF6 for the storage of almost any secondary    7325 1451
distribution entails that we only use MF4 for the neutron elastic 7325 1451
scattering distribution. All data are generated with Talys.       7325 1451
                                                                  7325 1451
- MT2      : Elastic angular distribution                         7325 1451
                                                                  7325 1451
The flag LTT=3 is used to indicate a switch at 20 MeV from a      7325 1451
Legendre representation to a tabulated representation. For        7325 1451
incident energies below 20 MeV, the Legendre coefficients are     7325 1451
given on a sufficiently precise energy grid. They are a sum of    7325 1451
calculated Legendre coefficients for compound nucleus and         7325 1451
shape-elastic scattering. For incident energies above 20 MeV,     7325 1451
relative angular distributions are tabulated on an angular grid.  7325 1451
                                                                  7325 1451
##### MF6: PRODUCT ENERGY-ANGLE DISTRIBUTIONS                     7325 1451
                                                                  7325 1451
In MF6 we store all secondary energy, angle, and energy-angle     7325 1451
distributions, as well as all residual and discrete + continuum   7325 1451
photon production cross sections. We thus do not use MF12-15 for  7325 1451
the photon production that accompanies each reaction. All data    7325 1451
are generated with Talys.                                         7325 1451
                                                                  7325 1451
- MT5      : (n,anything) yields and energy-angle distributions   7325 1451
                                                                  7325 1451
For energies below 20 MeV, MT5 contains the relative yields of    7325 1451
the (n,gamma x) reaction, where x may represent neutron, proton,  7325 1451
deuteron, triton, Helium-3 or alpha. Using the (n,gamma x) cross  7325 1451
section of MF3/MT3, the (n,gamma p), ..., (n,gamma alpha) cross   7325 1451
section can be recovered. For energies above 20 MeV, MT5 contains 7325 1451
the production yields of particles and residual products. It also 7325 1451
contains the secondary energy-angle distributions for all         7325 1451
particles and photons. First, the yields for neutrons are given   7325 1451
for the whole energy range. Next, on a secondary energy grid the  7325 1451
relative emission spectra are given together with the parameters  7325 1451
for the Kalbach systematics for angular distributions. Inelastic  7325 1451
scattering cross sections for discrete states have been broadened 7325 1451
and added to the continuum spectra. This procedure is repeated    7325 1451
for protons, deuterons, tritons, Helium-3, alpha particles and    7325 1451
photons. Finally, the residual production yields are given per    7325 1451
final product. All these yields and relative distributions can    7325 1451
be multiplied with the cross sections given in MF3/MT5 to get     7325 1451
the production cross sections and (double-)differential cross     7325 1451
sections.                                                         7325 1451
                                                                  7325 1451
- MT16     : (n,2n) energy-angle distr. and photon production     7325 1451
                                                                  7325 1451
First, for each type of outgoing particle, the (trivial) integer  7325 1451
particle yields are given. Next, on a sufficiently dense incident 7325 1451
energy grid the secondary energy-angle distributions are          7325 1451
specified by means of the relative emission spectra and the       7325 1451
parameters for the Kalbach systematics for angular distributions. 7325 1451
Next, the photon yield is tabulated as a function of incident     7325 1451
energy. For each incident energy, the photon production is given  7325 1451
for all discrete gamma lines present in the final nucleus. A      7325 1451
continuum photon distribution is added to this. We assume         7325 1451
isotropy for all produced gamma rays.                             7325 1451
